statement.p:
A k-form \alpha is called exact on a domain D if there
is a (k-1)-form \beta on D such that
\boxed{\alpha=d\beta.}

For example:

\begin{array}{c|c}
\text{Exact form} \amp \text{Means} \\ \hline
\omega=d\phi \amp \text{a 1-form is the derivative of a function}\\[1mm]
\Phi=d\omega \amp \text{a 2-form is the derivative of a 1-form}\\[1mm]
\Theta=d\Phi \amp \text{a 3-form is the derivative of a 2-form}
\end{array}

subsection.p:
For flux 2-forms in space,
\Phi=P\,dy\wedge dz+Q\,dz\wedge dx+R\,dx\wedge dy
is closed exactly when
\boxed{P_x+Q_y+R_z=0.}
In vector language, this says
\boxed{\nabla\cdot(P,Q,R)=0.}

This theorem contains a smoothness phrase for a reason. The cancellation in d^2=0 uses equality of mixed partial derivatives. Section showed a function
g(x,y)= \begin{cases} \dfrac{xy(x^2-y^2)}{x^2+y^2}, \amp (x,y)\ne(0,0),\\[2mm] 0, \amp (x,y)=(0,0), \end{cases}
for which g_{xy}(0,0)=-1, \qquad g_{yx}(0,0)=1. If we try to use the smooth-form rule at the origin without the smoothness, the usual cancellation fails. The identity d^2=0 is a theorem for smooth forms, not a license to ignore broken mixed partials.

Now integrate around the unit circle C:\quad \mathbf r(t)=(\cos t,\sin t), \qquad 0\le t\le2\pi. Along C, dx=-\sin t\,dt, \qquad dy=\cos t\,dt, and x^2+y^2=1. Thus
\mathbf r^*\alpha \amp= -\sin t(-\sin t\,dt)+\cos t(\cos t\,dt) \amp= dt.
So \boxed{\oint_C\alpha=2\pi.}

